There was two events that I thought was quite interesting.

37
00:03:02,420 --> 00:03:09,640
For example, one of it was Boris Johnson, big red bus with a gigantic letters of how much it's going to cost to.

38
00:03:10,300 --> 00:03:12,280
Sold to people comes in, yep.

39
00:03:12,280 --> 00:03:13,820
As well as...

40
00:03:13,820 --> 00:03:18,480
After the referendum, the biggest search was what is the EU?

41
00:03:18,480 --> 00:03:19,960
Yeah, exactly that.

42
00:03:19,960 --> 00:03:20,920
Yeah, exactly.

43
00:03:20,920 --> 00:03:22,560
You know, what...

44
00:03:22,560 --> 00:03:35,620
Is it a true representation of democracy when the people who voted and took part in the vote didn't have a clue or didn't even really care or didn't even really know what they were voting on?

45
00:03:37,260 --> 00:03:50,020
Yeah, that's definitely is a takeaway from, at least from direct democracy as we think about it now, and something we're aiming to fix with Issue Based Direct Democracy, or we believe we fixed with Issue Based Direct Democracy.

46
00:03:50,020 --> 00:03:52,360
I will definitely follow up on that aspect.

47
00:03:52,360 --> 00:04:00,460
Before we start with that, like a couple of years ago, we had an event on citizen juries, and Nicholas Groen had this group, which I find quite interesting.

48
00:04:00,460 --> 00:04:05,920
What we're seeking for in the system is the well-considered opinion of the population.

49
00:04:05,920 --> 00:04:08,420
Is that what you're thinking of as well?

50
00:04:08,420 --> 00:04:09,060
Yeah, 100%.

51
00:04:09,360 --> 00:04:15,960
I mean, we focus it through, I guess, the lens of specialization.

52
00:04:15,960 --> 00:04:21,820
You want people who specialize in the question to be answering the question.

53
00:04:21,839 --> 00:04:22,540
I see.

54
00:04:22,540 --> 00:04:29,640
So yeah, now we can start actually getting to, if I remember, you said Flux is an Issue Based Direct Democracy.

55
00:04:29,640 --> 00:04:31,420
What is an Issue Based Democracy?

56
00:04:31,680 --> 00:04:44,020
So, the philosophy we're calling Issue Based Direct Democracy is for what I call, I guess, a progression of a few of the thought processes around direct democracy.

57
00:04:44,020 --> 00:04:50,680
So, it combines, obviously, direct democracy that we know, being able to vote yes or no.

58
00:04:50,680 --> 00:04:53,980
But this comes with problems, which BIST has been discussing.

59
00:04:53,980 --> 00:04:55,680
People have to vote yes or no.

60
00:04:56,140 --> 00:04:58,160
They have to give a response.

61
00:04:58,160 --> 00:05:00,740
They might not be informed about the subject or they might not care about it.

62
00:05:01,060 --> 00:05:06,380
Also, in other countries, you don't have to vote, but in Australia, you have to vote.

63
00:05:06,380 --> 00:05:09,660
So, maybe I should make this clear for those who are overseas.

64
00:05:09,660 --> 00:05:12,400
In Australia, it is mandatory to vote.

65
00:05:12,400 --> 00:05:13,740
Right, I'm talking about something different.

66
00:05:13,740 --> 00:05:14,940
This would be direct democracy.

67
00:05:14,940 --> 00:05:15,940
Direct democracy.

68
00:05:15,940 --> 00:05:17,480
Not voting on politicians.

69
00:05:18,040 --> 00:05:23,500
So, in a direct democracy, for instance, Brexit vote, you had to vote yes or no.

70
00:05:23,500 --> 00:05:25,840
There was no option not to vote.

71
00:05:25,840 --> 00:05:28,740
There was no option to do anything else with your vote.

72
00:05:28,740 --> 00:05:29,840
So, this is where Flux comes in.

73
00:05:29,980 --> 00:05:31,420
So, we're not just a direct democracy.

74
00:05:31,420 --> 00:05:34,140
We've added in another element called liquid democracy.

75
00:05:34,140 --> 00:05:35,000
Liquid democracy.

76
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:47,040
So, this is when you don't know about the subject, but you do think it should be dealt with by professionals or by insightful people or scientists or however, you know, a leader that you trust.

77
00:05:47,040 --> 00:05:55,480
So, you can delegate on that one issue or in that one field to have someone else use your vote and tell you where it should go.

78
00:05:55,480 --> 00:05:56,400
So, that's the second portion.

79
00:05:56,400 --> 00:05:57,260
Where it should be directed to.

80
00:05:57,440 --> 00:06:00,440
So, where it should be directed, you delegate to them, they move it on.

81
00:06:00,440 --> 00:06:11,980
So, this cleans up a lot of the problems with direct democracy, but it also brings in, I guess, a few extra problems in that there's the hubris.

82
00:06:11,980 --> 00:06:16,820
People are just going to keep going to the same leader when it's not necessarily the best idea.

83
00:06:16,820 --> 00:06:20,200
Is that kind of related to the tribal effect that we're seeing?

84
00:06:20,200 --> 00:06:20,500
Yeah.

85
00:06:20,500 --> 00:06:22,400
I mean, it'd be a much smaller version right now.

86
00:06:22,400 --> 00:06:34,760
We see it in the whole party, but you'd still go, you know, Dr. Carl is my science and tech guy, and he always will be for the next 20 years, because I know him, but he might not still have the best ideas.

87
00:06:34,760 --> 00:06:40,220
So what you actually want is a way for people to specialise and hyper specialise in their skills.

88
00:06:41,500 --> 00:06:48,680
So the other addition, apart from liquid democracy, is the ability in a vote where none of the answers are any good to you.

89
00:06:49,160 --> 00:07:04,760
The addition, the ability to not vote at all, and abstain from voting, and then you would store up a little bit of that vote's energy, and then you can put it towards your own novel idea, or something you're really, really passionate about.

90
00:07:04,760 --> 00:07:08,680
Because yeah, we don't want, we also want a reward.

91
00:07:10,480 --> 00:07:14,100
We don't want to incentivise people just giving away their vote.

92
00:07:14,100 --> 00:07:18,040
obviously, liquid democracy is easier, but it might not be the best answer for you.

93
00:07:18,040 --> 00:07:28,880
So in other words, it sounds like you're almost trying to, like, get people to abstain from certain issues if they are not passionate enough about that particular issue.

94
00:07:28,880 --> 00:07:29,660
A hundred percent.

95
00:07:29,660 --> 00:07:52,300
Like I remembered, you made an analogy between those who are Christian, and those who are atheists, and in regard to, say, the abortion debate, if everybody has the same amount of vote, they may not choose to vote in a way that is suitable for the entire nation, but instead you want to get them to actually make a decision of what they care more about.

96
00:07:52,300 --> 00:07:57,220
Maybe they care more about religious right rather than banning abortion completely.

97
00:07:57,220 --> 00:08:00,240
So maybe you could tell me a bit more in your words.

98
00:08:00,240 --> 00:08:02,780
Is that the angle?

99
00:08:02,780 --> 00:08:07,640
Yeah, I don't remember the specific analogy, but I'll pick it up.

100
00:08:07,640 --> 00:08:18,460
I think it's that the, yeah, you know, it's, or even the alternative of maybe you believe in every single Christian value except for being anti-abortion.

101
00:08:18,460 --> 00:08:32,760
So even taking it from the other side, and then it's like, you would have to be right now, if you wanted to have support for all of your other 49 values, you have to, by default, support that other one.

102
00:08:32,760 --> 00:08:44,540
And that's not necessarily what we want, because that might, you might not truly view that as the best, you know, let's say Christian values, sticky one to stay with, but let's go with it.

103
00:08:44,540 --> 00:08:53,120
You know, Christian values of kindness and humility and being kind to others, you might see them being upheld in every other way, except for this one.

104
00:08:53,120 --> 00:09:01,540
So it's kind of like similar to having to choose a cable TV packaging, but like a lot of them forces you to also choose.

105
00:09:01,540 --> 00:09:04,060
Hey, there's an analogy I feel much safer going into.

106
00:09:04,060 --> 00:09:05,940
Yes, exactly.

107
00:09:05,940 --> 00:09:10,040
And this is, oh, that makes me feel so much better.

108
00:09:10,040 --> 00:09:14,900
Right now in your voting, you could specialize just in the sporting package.

109
00:09:15,520 --> 00:09:15,700
Yes.

110
00:09:15,700 --> 00:09:16,320
And you would be...

111
00:09:16,320 --> 00:09:17,720
Everybody wants the sport.

112
00:09:17,720 --> 00:09:18,900
You just want that sports package.

113
00:09:18,900 --> 00:09:20,480
You don't care about anything else.

114
00:09:20,480 --> 00:09:31,140
And you would be rewarded by, instead of saving money for not buying those other packages, you would be rewarded by getting more political energy that you can spend on sports related things.

115
00:09:31,140 --> 00:09:32,360
I like that.

116
00:09:32,360 --> 00:09:37,760
Oh, thank you for giving me that analogy rather than me tiptoeing through Christian values.

117
00:09:38,800 --> 00:09:41,020
But yeah, that's a really great analogy though.

118
00:09:41,580 --> 00:09:51,640
Okay, so I think now you explained a bit more about Issue Based Democracy, and so the audience will at least know what IBDD stands for.

119
00:09:51,640 --> 00:09:59,580
But there's also this other model which you would have heard of quite a bit, and I've mentioned not too long ago, about Citizen Juries.

120
00:09:59,580 --> 00:10:02,660
And Flux, on the other hand, implements IBDD.

121
00:10:02,660 --> 00:10:06,320
So I'm kind of curious, why didn't Flux use Citizen Juries?

122
00:10:06,320 --> 00:10:07,180
Why IBDD?

123
00:10:09,480 --> 00:10:14,940
I'm laughing about this because I was jokingly being a little rough on Citizen Juries.

124
00:10:15,500 --> 00:10:25,120
So Citizen Juries and IBDD, I think come from the same place in that they're both trying to fix bad representation.

125
00:10:25,120 --> 00:10:30,580
They don't want us to be represented poorly by people who aren't us, the people.

126
00:10:30,580 --> 00:10:33,120
So in that way, I think Citizen Juries are really great.

127
00:10:33,420 --> 00:10:40,160
They empower ordinary people who are interested and don't actually want to see the change happen.

128
00:10:40,160 --> 00:10:48,000
But what they don't do is they don't reward specialization, and they don't reward someone getting the correct answer.

129
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:53,380
Someone doing really well in a Citizen Jury may never be called up again.

130
00:10:53,380 --> 00:10:55,920
And that's something Flux wants to limit with IBDD.

131
00:10:55,920 --> 00:10:56,680
So we focus on-

132
00:10:56,740 --> 00:11:08,060
It's kind of similar to how you notice with the modern day society, everybody is starting to hyper specialize in their own engineering, doctors, fields and so on.

133
00:11:08,060 --> 00:11:11,020
Yes, that's almost perfectly it.

134
00:11:12,420 --> 00:11:16,800
If everybody's specializing in their fields, we want to reward that.

135
00:11:17,380 --> 00:11:35,360
We don't want to try and create these representatives that are really great at most things, or jack of all trades at most things, when we could have masters at everything, delivering the results that are given to, you know, that are confirmed by the people, as opposed to...

136
00:11:35,360 --> 00:11:53,480
So, maybe the other analogy you could probably make as well is the pattern system, and how a lot of the issue with the pattern system is that those that do the revoke of the pattern systems are not always the same people that are specialized in understanding how it works, especially when you put it to the jury system.

137
00:11:53,480 --> 00:11:53,920
What do you mean?

138
00:11:54,200 --> 00:12:11,260
At the moment, if I understand, when you have pattern conflicts, people need to call up experts to talk to the juries, but a lot of the issues is that the juries, in a very short amount of time, have to pick up the network stack, all sorts, computer theory, etc.

139
00:12:11,680 --> 00:12:24,880
And this can, in some ways, overwhelm the jury system in trying to deal with making the right choices of who to order pattern to, or whether the pattern is valid or not.

140
00:12:24,880 --> 00:12:26,120
Yeah, I think so.

141
00:12:26,120 --> 00:12:27,000
And I think it's like...

142
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:37,260
And I think this ties into the aspects of what you're trying to say about the need for hyper-specialization on maybe even on the complex issues.

143
00:12:37,260 --> 00:12:38,740
Yes, that's exactly it.

144
00:12:38,780 --> 00:12:40,100
It's like, you know, you could...

145
00:12:40,100 --> 00:12:49,520
You can hope that, especially in this patent case, you can hope that a jury will be able to see the just thing to do.

146
00:12:49,520 --> 00:12:50,720
And, you know, they might be...

147
00:12:50,720 --> 00:12:58,780
If someone can explain it to them correctly, they can make the correct decision because they have less...

148
00:12:58,780 --> 00:12:59,440
You know, they don't get...

149
00:12:59,440 --> 00:13:04,980
They have no dog in the fight, so they're going to make the correct decision because that is their task as the jury.

150
00:13:04,980 --> 00:13:15,160
But you're adding in the fact that they know that they can be bamboozled or just jargoned until they don't actually know what they're looking at, whereas that's something you could never get...

151
00:13:15,160 --> 00:13:17,100
You couldn't do to a specialist.

152
00:13:18,160 --> 00:13:23,340
So instead of having that jury, you have a specialist everybody trusts, and they can't be bamboozled, hopefully.

153
00:13:23,340 --> 00:13:27,700
Of course, the biggest issue is that we delegate and our trust to a politician.

154
00:13:27,700 --> 00:13:32,800
What's not to say that this isn't going to happen as well with those we delegate our trust to?

155
00:13:33,620 --> 00:13:41,060
Yeah, that is, like I was saying, a flaw in liquid democracy that used the term hubris.

156
00:13:41,060 --> 00:13:42,340
But also that...

157
00:13:42,360 --> 00:13:44,300
Liquid democracy, IBDD?

158
00:13:44,300 --> 00:13:45,380
Yes, it's within IBDD.

159
00:13:45,380 --> 00:13:46,760
Oh, within IBDD.

160
00:13:46,760 --> 00:13:48,500
So that's a problem.

161
00:13:48,860 --> 00:13:54,360
It is great that you can delegate to someone, but they can either get lazy or they can be corrupted.

162
00:13:54,360 --> 00:14:00,680
The best thing about IB or within a digital liquid democracy is the second they do that, you pull that power back.

163
00:14:01,220 --> 00:14:01,600
I see.

164
00:14:01,600 --> 00:14:07,600
So there's a accountability feedback loop that you're saying that is missing from the original.

165
00:14:07,600 --> 00:14:12,080
Liquid democracy that was applied by the Pirate Party of another country, if I remember.

166
00:14:12,080 --> 00:14:17,900
They tried to test it, but pure liquid democracy, but they had a bit of issue that you were talking about.

167
00:14:17,900 --> 00:14:18,900
Yeah, actually.

168
00:14:19,280 --> 00:14:26,880
What would you say in this IBDD, Issue Based Direct Democracy is an evolution of liquid democracy?

169
00:14:28,580 --> 00:14:30,000
Yeah.

170
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:39,560
evolutions, maybe not the term I'd use, just liquid democracy is just one facet within IBDD that serves a purpose.

171
00:14:39,560 --> 00:14:53,620
It serves the purpose to remove the staticness of direct democracy, and make it a bit more fluid, and make it sure that people who care and people who want to help can be empowered.

172
00:14:53,620 --> 00:14:58,840
But it's not so much an evolution in that it's a logical progression of...

173
00:14:58,840 --> 00:14:59,420
progression.

174
00:14:59,460 --> 00:15:10,560
Because they serve separate purposes, and the three keys, direct democracy, liquid democracy, and the issue based vote sharing, they all serve different purposes.

175
00:15:10,560 --> 00:15:12,740
They're not necessarily like a linear thing.

176
00:15:12,740 --> 00:15:13,860
I think that's pretty sensible.

177
00:15:15,800 --> 00:15:17,860
So people are unengaged.

178
00:15:17,860 --> 00:15:20,260
They're not aware that they're not in a democracy.

179
00:15:20,260 --> 00:15:22,240
The media doesn't tell them the choices.

180
00:15:22,240 --> 00:15:35,540
Even if I like this whole concept of the Flux IPDD system, how do you get people to use it if they're not aware of this system, or could find it difficult to understand it?

181
00:15:35,540 --> 00:15:37,920
It's a difficult one.

182
00:15:37,920 --> 00:15:40,660
I mean, obviously, we're looking at the most straightforward thing.

183
00:15:41,060 --> 00:15:42,600
Get a member represented.

184
00:15:43,260 --> 00:15:46,160
An elected and a representative into parliament.

185
00:15:46,160 --> 00:15:55,120
So obviously, election campaigns and running successful ones of those are the black and white answer to that question.

186
00:15:55,120 --> 00:15:55,960
That's our hope.

187
00:15:55,960 --> 00:15:58,520
That's our goal for it all.

188
00:15:58,520 --> 00:16:10,100
Secondary to that would be we're hoping to release an app that allows people to mirror parliament and have their vote and then have it displayed according to their community.

189
00:16:10,460 --> 00:16:19,460
And we're hoping that that as a method of people lobbying their representatives and the idea could really catch on.

190
00:16:19,460 --> 00:16:26,800
The idea that what's happening in parliament, I'll have a look, I'll vote on it and I'll push it to my friends and more importantly my MP.

191
00:16:26,800 --> 00:16:29,000
Yeah, that's the stepping stone to getting to people that are really interested.

192
00:16:29,000 --> 00:16:29,920
I certainly hope it does.

193
00:16:30,340 --> 00:16:40,040
So, well, once you do get it in, like every kind of curious to know about the algorithms and like, how would these issues be selected?

194
00:16:40,040 --> 00:16:42,260
Like as representative as possible.

195
00:16:42,260 --> 00:16:42,620
Yeah.

196
00:16:42,620 --> 00:16:53,780
So initially, I imagine with one MP, a lot of the time we're just straight reacting to other parties, and we're allowing every person in our electorate to vote yes or no, to what other political parties want.

197
00:16:53,780 --> 00:17:06,579
But what you can do with when you elect not to vote on things in that parliament, you store up that energy and then you can put that up into like, I guess, a separate voting mechanism in the flux ecosystem.

198
00:17:06,579 --> 00:17:18,220
So yeah, you could renege from making up these numbers, but 50 votes and that should afford you enough to be able to put forward a piece of legislation that you yourself can write up.

199
00:17:18,220 --> 00:17:21,500
And then yeah, everyone can vote on that from just within your community.

200
00:17:22,339 --> 00:17:23,579
Nice, nice.

201
00:17:23,579 --> 00:17:27,640
What is the theory and the philosophy behind IBDD and flux?

202
00:17:27,640 --> 00:17:39,980
So we now explored citizen juries and flux, but I'd be curious to know between flux and IBDD, like how, what is the relation of IBDD to flux?

203
